data.content:
# EF Core 10 Breaking Changes for Your Code

## 1. `SetPropertyCalls<T>` → `SetPropertyBuilder<T>`

The type was **renamed**. Every explicit reference breaks — especially your expression-tree code.

**Fix:**

```csharp
Expression<Func<SetPropertyBuilder<Blog>, SetPropertyBuilder<Blog>>> setters =
    s => s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
if (nameChanged)
{
    var blogParameter = Expression.Parameter(typeof(Blog), "b");
    setters = Expression.Lambda<Func<SetPropertyBuilder<Blog>, SetPropertyBuilder<Blog>>>(
        Expression.Call(
            instance: setters.Body,
            methodName: nameof(SetPropertyBuilder<Blog>.SetProperty),
            typeArguments: new[] { typeof(string) },
            arguments: new Expression[]
            {
                Expression.Lambda<Func<Blog, string>>(
                    Expression.Property(blogParameter, nameof(Blog.Name)), blogParameter),
                Expression.Constant("foo")
            }),
        setters.Parameters);
}
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(setters);
```

Find-and-replace `SetPropertyCalls<` → `SetPropertyBuilder<` across the solution.

---

## 2. Complex-type column naming convention changed

EF Core 10 changed the default column name separator for complex properties from `_` (underscore) to `.` (dot). For example, `ShippingAddress_Street` becomes `ShippingAddress.Street`. This **breaks existing databases** silently — queries target wrong column names.

**Fix** — pin the old convention to avoid a migration/rename:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sb => {
        sb.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
        // repeat for each property
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, sb => {
        sb.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types (Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City):
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, pb => {
        pb.ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress, ab => {
            ab.Property(a => a.City)
              .HasColumnName("Payment_BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

Or apply globally via a model convention to keep underscore separators for all complex properties, avoiding per-property annotations.

---

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `CommandSource` parameter

EF Core 10 added a `CommandSource commandSource` parameter to the command-interception methods on the diagnostics logger interface.

**Fix:**

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
        DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        CommandSource commandSource)   // ← new parameter
    { /* logging */ }

    // Update all other methods in the interface similarly
}
```

---

### Quick checklist

| Pattern | Search for | Replace with |
|---|---|---|
| Rename | `SetPropertyCalls<` | `SetPropertyBuilder<` |
| Columns | complex-type properties | add `HasColumnName()` or global convention |
| Logger | old diagnostic signatures | add `CommandSource` parameter |
